Narrator: FIRST INTO
THE TANK IS ONE DAD'S SOLUTION

00:02:20,574 --> 00:02:23,310
TO MAKE BABIES'
FEEDING TIME EASIER.

00:02:23,310 --> 00:02:26,013
♪♪

00:02:30,150 --> 00:02:33,120
HELLO, SHARKS.
MY NAME IS MARTIN HILL.

00:02:33,120 --> 00:02:35,622
AND I AM THE OWNER AND CREATOR
OF THE BEEBO.

00:02:35,622 --> 00:02:37,791
I AM SEEKING
A $200,000 INVESTMENT

00:02:37,791 --> 00:02:42,029
IN EXCHANGE FOR A 20%
EQUITY STAKE IN MY COMPANY.

00:02:42,029 --> 00:02:44,598
PARENTS HAVE BEEN BOTTLE-FEEDING
THEIR BABIES THE SAME WAY

00:02:44,598 --> 00:02:48,702
FOR OVER 150 YEARS -- BABY IN
ONE HAND, BOTTLE IN THE OTHER.

00:02:48,702 --> 00:02:50,504
I HAVE CREATED A PRODUCT

00:02:50,504 --> 00:02:52,406
THAT ENHANCES THE WAY
PARENTS BOTTLE-FEED,

00:02:52,406 --> 00:02:55,409
TAKING THIS PRECIOUS MOMENT
AND MAKING IT BETTER.

00:02:55,409 --> 00:02:59,212
I AM VERY PROUD
TO INTRODUCE YOU TO THE BEEBO --

00:02:59,212 --> 00:03:01,314
A BETTER WAY TO BOTTLE-FEED.

00:03:01,314 --> 00:03:02,716
[ GREINER CHUCKLES ]
OH...MY...GOD.

00:03:02,716 --> 00:03:04,584
[ LAUGHTER ]

00:03:04,584 --> 00:03:05,786
O'Leary: OH, YEAH.

00:03:05,786 --> 00:03:07,587
Hill: THE BEEBO
IS PEDIATRICIAN-APPROVED

00:03:07,587 --> 00:03:09,189
AND EASY TO USE.

00:03:09,189 --> 00:03:12,793
YOU SIMPLY PLACE THE BEEBO
OVER EITHER SHOULDER...

00:03:12,793 --> 00:03:15,595
INSERT YOUR BABY'S BOTTLE...

00:03:15,595 --> 00:03:18,665
AND THEN ROTATE
TO THE DESIRED FEEDING ANGLE.

00:03:18,665 --> 00:03:20,834
HMM.
YOU CAN EVEN ROTATE THE BOTTLE
UP AND OUT OF THE WAY

00:03:20,834 --> 00:03:23,170
FOR BURPING OR PLAYTIME.

00:03:23,170 --> 00:03:25,338
THE BEEBO FREES UP A HAND
DURING FEEDING,

00:03:25,338 --> 00:03:28,175
ALLOWING YOU
TO READ TO YOUR BABY,

00:03:28,175 --> 00:03:31,878
CARESS YOUR BABY, EVEN ENJOY
FAMILY MEALS TOGETHER.

00:03:31,878 --> 00:03:35,449
SO, SHARKS, WHO WANTS TO JOIN ME
IN GIVING PARENTS AND BABIES

00:03:35,449 --> 00:03:37,818
THAT HELPING HAND
THEY NEED AND DESERVE?

00:03:37,818 --> 00:03:40,454
Greiner: AH.
I'VE GOT SAMPLES FOR YOU.

00:03:40,454 --> 00:03:42,289
ASHTON, ISN'T YOUR BABY HERE?
WHY DON'T YOU GO GRAB HER?

00:03:42,289 --> 00:03:44,825
I'M PRETTY SURE MY BABY'S
A "NOT ON-CAMERA" BABY.

00:03:44,825 --> 00:03:47,828
[ LAUGHTER ]
I'M FAIRLY CERTAIN THAT MY BABY
ISN'T PART OF THE EQUATION.

00:03:47,828 --> 00:03:49,496
OH, THANK YOU. OH, OH,
LET ME GRAB ONE FOR LORI.
YOU'RE VERY WELCOME.

00:03:49,496 --> 00:03:51,064
SHE HAS A HARD TIME REACHING.
THANK YOU.

00:03:51,064 --> 00:03:53,100
THANK YOU.
IF YOU JUST HOLD ON
TO THEM FOR ONE SECOND,

00:03:53,100 --> 00:03:55,469
I'LL SHOW YOU THE -- THE BEST,
EASIEST WAY TO USE THEM.

00:03:55,469 --> 00:03:57,204
SOME PEOPLE LIKE TO PUT IT
A LITTLE BIT LOW...

00:03:57,204 --> 00:03:59,172
[ LAUGHS ]
...BECAUSE OF
WHAT IT LOOKS LIKE.

00:03:59,172 --> 00:04:01,908
[ CHUCKLES ] SO...

00:04:01,908 --> 00:04:04,444
Kutcher: HOW MANY
DIFFERENT KINDS OF BOTTLES

00:04:04,444 --> 00:04:06,313
CAN YOU USE FOR THIS?
LIKE, CERTAIN BABIES
LOVE THE DR. BROWN'S.

00:04:06,313 --> 00:04:08,115
MM-HMM.
SOME LIKE THOSE COMOTOMOS.

00:04:08,115 --> 00:04:09,449
MAN,
YOU KNOW YOUR BOTTLES.

00:04:09,449 --> 00:04:12,352
HEY, LISTEN. I'M ON --
I'M ON -- I'M ON DAD DUTY.

00:04:12,352 --> 00:04:15,155
SO, THIS IS MADE
OUT OF A VERY SOFT SKIN

00:04:15,155 --> 00:04:17,190
SO THAT IT'S WATERTIGHT,
FLEXIBLE FOAM.

00:04:17,190 --> 00:04:18,658
MARTIN, LET ME --
LET ME HAVE THE KID.

00:04:18,658 --> 00:04:20,594
IT'S BASICALLY
AN EXTRA HAND.

00:04:20,594 --> 00:04:22,896
CARLOS OR BOB?
YEAH, I'LL GO WITH THIS.

00:04:22,896 --> 00:04:24,331
YOU KNOW.
[ LAUGHTER ]

00:04:24,331 --> 00:04:25,165
ASHTON,
YOU'RE A FATHER RIGHT NOW.

00:04:25,165 --> 00:04:26,566
WHY DON'T YOU
CHECK THIS OUT?

00:04:26,566 --> 00:04:28,802
I-I...
YEAH, THAT'S WHAT
I'M TALKING ABOUT.

00:04:28,802 --> 00:04:31,805
GAME ON.
YOU LOOK GOOD.

00:04:31,805 --> 00:04:33,707
YOU'RE A LITTLE...
[ SIGHS ]
[ LAUGHS ]

00:04:33,707 --> 00:04:35,876
[ LAUGHS ]

00:04:35,876 --> 00:04:36,977
I LIKE IT.

00:04:36,977 --> 00:04:38,745
[ SIGHS ]
GET IT.

00:04:38,745 --> 00:04:40,914
THERE WE GO.
AND THIS IS FOR NEXT TIME
WHEN YOU HAVE TWINS.

00:04:40,914 --> 00:04:42,149
[ LAUGHS ]
Hill: THERE YOU GO.

00:04:42,149 --> 00:04:43,884
THERE WE GO.
Hill: WE DO GET --

00:04:43,884 --> 00:04:45,485
DOUBLE DUTY.
WE DO GET A LOT OF PEOPLE
WITH TWINS BUYING THIS.

00:04:45,485 --> 00:04:47,154
MARTIN, HOW DID YOU COME UP
WITH THIS?

00:04:47,154 --> 00:04:49,122
I'M AN ELECTRICAL ENGINEER
BY TRADE.

00:04:49,122 --> 00:04:52,492
MY LITTLE BOY, JACOB,
HE -- HE WENT THROUGH A PHASE

00:04:52,492 --> 00:04:54,394
OF REALLY STRUGGLING
WITH HIS BOTTLE,

00:04:54,394 --> 00:04:58,165
SO I CAME UP WITH THIS IDEA
BECAUSE HE WAS HIS MOST RELAXED

00:04:58,165 --> 00:04:59,499
WHEN I WAS READING A BOOK
TO HIM.

00:04:59,499 --> 00:05:01,968
I MADE MY PROTOTYPE
IN MY GARAGE,

00:05:01,968 --> 00:05:05,138
I STARTED USING IT, AND EVERY
TIME HE'D SUCK HIS BOTTLE DRY.

00:05:05,138 --> 00:05:06,706
HOW MUCH HAVE YOU SOLD?

00:05:06,706 --> 00:05:09,042
WE'VE SOLD ABOUT $20,000 WORTH
SINCE FEBRUARY.

00:05:09,042 --> 00:05:12,479
AND HOW MUCH DOES EACH UNIT SELL
FOR, AND WHAT DO THEY COST YOU?
WHAT IS YOUR COST PER UNIT?

00:05:12,479 --> 00:05:15,248
SURE, THE MSRP IS $39.95,

00:05:15,248 --> 00:05:18,585
AND THE MANUFACTURED COST
PER GOODS SO FAR PER UNIT TO ME

00:05:18,585 --> 00:05:20,453
IS $10.86.

00:05:20,453 --> 00:05:23,957
SO, IN FEBRUARY,
WE ONLY SOLD ABOUT $1,800.

00:05:23,957 --> 00:05:26,493
IN MARCH,
WE MORE THAN DOUBLED THAT.

00:05:26,493 --> 00:05:29,362
WE ARE STARTING TO GET KIND OF
INUNDATED WITH BUYERS RIGHT NOW.

00:05:29,362 --> 00:05:32,999
WE'VE BEEN CONTACTED
BY SOME BIG-BOX RETAIL.

00:05:32,999 --> 00:05:34,467
AND YOU HAVE NOTHING
IN RETAIL NOW?

00:05:34,467 --> 00:05:36,169
NO, NOTHING.

00:05:36,169 --> 00:05:37,404
CAN I SEE A PACKAGE,
MARTIN?

00:05:37,404 --> 00:05:38,738
YEAH, SURE.

00:05:38,738 --> 00:05:40,540
Greiner: DID YOU DO
ALL OF THE PACKAGING YOURSELF --

00:05:40,540 --> 00:05:41,541
THE DESIGNING
OF THE PACKAGING?

00:05:41,541 --> 00:05:42,576
I HAD A LOT OF SAY IN IT.

00:05:42,576 --> 00:05:44,711
IT DOESN'T REALLY TELL YOU
WHAT IT IS.

00:05:44,711 --> 00:05:46,379
IT'S HARD.

00:05:46,379 --> 00:05:48,648
I MEAN, I THINK YOU'D STRUGGLE
WITH THIS PACKAGING IN RETAIL.

00:05:48,648 --> 00:05:49,883
THAT'S PART OF THE FUNDING.

00:05:49,883 --> 00:05:52,118
YOU KNOW, WE'RE GONNA DO
A WHOLE BRAND REFRESH.

00:05:52,118 --> 00:05:54,120
O'Leary: IS YOUR PATENT
ISSUED RIGHT NOW?

00:05:54,120 --> 00:05:55,689
THE UTILITY PATENT
IS FULLY ISSUED.

00:05:55,689 --> 00:05:57,591
WHY DID YOU NAME IT "BEEBO"?
[ CHUCKLES ]

00:05:57,591 --> 00:05:59,626
SO, WHEN I INVENTED
MY FIRST PROTOTYPE,

00:05:59,626 --> 00:06:01,428
I USED TO CALL IT "THE BOOBY."

00:06:01,428 --> 00:06:03,563
OH, "THE BOOBY." [ LAUGHS ]
BOOBY -- I LIKE BOOBY --
I LIKE BOOBY BETTER.

00:06:03,563 --> 00:06:04,764
SO, THAT GOT SHOT DOWN
BY MY WIFE.

00:06:04,764 --> 00:06:05,832
I BET.
[ Laughing ] YEAH.

00:06:05,832 --> 00:06:06,867
IT'S A GOOD NAME.
[ LAUGHS ]

00:06:06,867 --> 00:06:08,468
IT IS. I THOUGHT SO, TOO.

00:06:08,468 --> 00:06:10,036
O'Leary: I-I LIKE THIS PRODUCT.
IT'S VERY SIMPLE.

00:06:10,036 --> 00:06:13,206
THE MESSAGING IS WEAK
ON THE RETAIL PACKAGE,

00:06:13,206 --> 00:06:15,208
BUT I THINK THE UTILITY OF IT
MAKES A LOT OF SENSE.

00:06:15,208 --> 00:06:18,378
IN MY BABY-FEEDING DAYS,
I REALLY HAD A LOT OF TROUBLE

00:06:18,378 --> 00:06:20,247
WITH THE WHOLE DEAL
WITH THE BOTTLE.

00:06:20,247 --> 00:06:21,715
I'LL MAKE YOU AN OFFER.

00:06:23,116 --> 00:06:26,620
I'LL GIVE YOU THE $200,000
FOR 33.3%.

00:06:26,620 --> 00:06:28,455
I THINK THE PRODUCT
IN RETAIL

00:06:28,455 --> 00:06:30,624
WILL BE SUCCESSFUL
AFTER BEING REPACKAGED.

00:06:30,624 --> 00:06:33,260
YOU'RE GONNA NEED MORE CASH.
BUT I LIKE IT.

00:06:33,260 --> 00:06:35,028
IT'S -- THAT'S A VERY SIMPLE
DEAL, STRAIGHT UP.

00:06:35,028 --> 00:06:37,831
I'LL TAKE 1/3 OF THE BUSINESS.
I'LL GIVE YOU $200,000.

00:06:37,831 --> 00:06:40,533
Kutcher: HOW MUCH OF YOUR OWN
MONEY HAVE YOU INVESTED IN THIS,

00:06:40,533 --> 00:06:43,470
AND WHAT ARE YOUR PROJECTIONS
ON SALES FOR THE NEXT YEAR?

00:06:43,470 --> 00:06:48,074
SO, WE'VE INVESTED
ABOUT $180,000 FROM DAY ONE.

00:06:48,074 --> 00:06:50,176
AND YOUR PROJECTIONS
OVER THE NEXT YEAR?

00:06:50,176 --> 00:06:53,914
OKAY, SO, MY GOAL FOR YEAR ONE
IS 14,000 UNITS.

00:06:53,914 --> 00:06:55,482
THE REASON WHY THAT'S THERE

00:06:55,482 --> 00:06:57,717
IS BECAUSE OF
MANUFACTURING CONSTRAINTS.

00:06:57,717 --> 00:06:59,819
RIGHT NOW, WE ONLY HAVE
ONE SET OF MOLDS.

00:06:59,819 --> 00:07:01,254
AND THEN NEXT YEAR,

00:07:01,254 --> 00:07:04,324
MY GOAL IS TO START RAMPING UP
MORE INTO BIG-BOX RETAIL.

00:07:04,324 --> 00:07:07,327
MARTIN, LOOK, YOU'VE DONE
AN AMAZING JOB WITH IT.

00:07:07,327 --> 00:07:09,896
I ADMIRE THE FACT
THAT YOU PUT UP $180,000

00:07:09,896 --> 00:07:11,031
TO START THIS BUSINESS.

00:07:11,031 --> 00:07:12,432
I LOVE PEOPLE
THAT ARE ALL-IN.

00:07:12,432 --> 00:07:13,700
YEP.

00:07:13,700 --> 00:07:16,002
IT'S BEEN A LONG TIME
SINCE I'VE HAD A BABY,

00:07:16,002 --> 00:07:17,837
AND I HAD EVERY PROBLEM
YOU CAN IMAGINE

00:07:17,837 --> 00:07:19,572
AND FOUND WAYS TO SOLVE IT,
YOU KNOW?

00:07:19,572 --> 00:07:20,707
YEAH.

00:07:20,707 --> 00:07:24,411
I NEVER REMEMBER THIS
BEING A PROBLEM FOR ME.

00:07:24,411 --> 00:07:26,947
I JUST DON'T SEE THE PAIN.
I'M OUT.

00:07:26,947 --> 00:07:29,115
ALL RIGHT, THANK YOU.

00:07:30,583 --> 00:07:33,086
♪♪

00:07:33,086 --> 00:07:35,422
YOU KNOW, I THINK --
I THINK IT'S A GREAT PRODUCT.

00:07:35,422 --> 00:07:38,625
